01:48.951 --> 01:53.263
You've just heard some words and music
written by Rodgers and Hart.

01:53.322 --> 01:57.134
This is the Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer
sound stage number one.

01:57.193 --> 02:00.333
In this film, Mickey Rooney
will portray Larry Hart,

02:00.396 --> 02:03.707
or Lorenz Hart, as the song sheets read,

02:03.766 --> 02:05.973
and I am Richard Rodgers.

02:07.403 --> 02:12.352
If in telling you about Larry
I talk quite a bit about myself,

02:12.408 --> 02:15.355
it's because there hasn't been
a day in my life

02:15.411 --> 02:18.620
that didn't have something
to do with Larry Hart.

02:18.681 --> 02:21.355
I'm almost sorry to say

02:21.417 --> 02:26.457
there were none of the standard trials
and tribulations you'd ordinarily expect.

02:27.556 --> 02:31.800
In fact, we were just two lucky fellows
who had success very young.

02:31.861 --> 02:34.364
From a dramatic standpoint,

02:34.430 --> 02:37.968
we didn't even have the advantage
of being very poor.

02:38.034 --> 02:40.241
We weren't very rich, either.

02:41.570 --> 02:43.447
When I first met Larry,

02:43.506 --> 02:48.785
he had already acquired quite a reputation
at Columbia University as a poet and wit,

02:48.844 --> 02:51.051
and I was a little scared.

02:51.113 --> 02:54.560
Anyhow, one day Herb Fields,
a mutual friend of ours

02:54.617 --> 02:57.427
who later wrote the books
for some of our shows,

02:57.486 --> 02:59.022
<i>arranged a meeting.</i>

02:59.088 --> 03:00.567
- Is this it?
- Yep.

03:00.623 --> 03:02.034
Maybe we ought to come back
some other time.

03:02.091 --> 03:03.627
- Oh, relax, will you?
- Yeah. But you think...

03:03.693 --> 03:05.468
Look, you wanna do a show with him,
don't you?

03:05.528 --> 03:06.666
- Oh sure, sure.
- All right, then.

03:06.729 --> 03:09.300
Meet him,
play a couple of songs and you're in.

03:10.366 --> 03:12.243
- Hi, Herb.
- Hi, Larry.

03:12.301 --> 03:13.507
- Come on in.
- Thanks.

03:13.569 --> 03:14.843
Larry, I'd like
to have you meet Dick Rodgers.

03:14.904 --> 03:16.110
You know,
the fellow I was telling you about.

03:16.172 --> 03:17.276
Oh, hiya, Dick.

03:17.339 --> 03:19.444
Heard a lot about you.
You're the fellow who writes music, eh?

03:19.508 --> 03:21.613
- Well, I...
- Come on in. Make yourself at home.

03:21.677 --> 03:24.283
You hungry? Want something to eat?
How about some nuts?

03:24.346 --> 03:25.757
- Oh, no. Thanks.
- Apples? Oranges?

03:25.815 --> 03:26.850
- How about a piece of coffee cake?
- No...

03:26.916 --> 03:28.987
Corned beef sandwich? I'll send out,
get a corned beef sandwich.

03:29.051 --> 03:30.689
- No, thanks very much, anyway.
- Smoke? Cigar?

03:30.753 --> 03:32.061
- Light ones? Dark ones?
- I never use them.

03:32.121 --> 03:35.398
How about you, Herb? That's right.
You don't smoke, do you?

03:41.430 --> 03:42.738
<i>Go ahead.</i>

03:49.472 --> 03:51.008
Play something.

03:57.446 --> 03:58.754
<i>Go ahead.</i>

04:27.409 --> 04:30.015
Hey, hey, Herb, I got a new rhyme for you.
What rhymes with Coolidge?

04:30.079 --> 04:31.149
- Coolidge?
- Yeah.

04:31.213 --> 04:33.693
- Nothing rhymes with Coolidge.
- You wanna bet?

04:33.749 --> 04:35.387
- Coolidge?
- Sure, say it over to yourself.

04:35.451 --> 04:37.362
Coolidge, Coolidge, Coolidge.
Come on, quick.

04:37.419 --> 04:38.625
Oh, I'm ashamed of you.

04:38.687 --> 04:41.133
When you speak of Coolidge,
he deserves a eulogy.

04:41.190 --> 04:43.033
Coolidge he, eulogy.

04:43.459 --> 04:44.870
Hey, that's very good, Larry.

04:44.927 --> 04:46.531
That's all.

04:46.595 --> 04:48.165
Herb, did you read this article yet?

04:48.230 --> 04:50.608
- No, I didn't.
- It's not bad at all.

05:30.472 --> 05:33.112
Operator, give me Trafalgar 4599, please.

05:36.345 --> 05:40.919
Hello, Jack? This is Larry Hart.
Have you got that book of Heine's in yet?

05:40.983 --> 05:44.260
No, no, no. Not the translation.
That was the later edition.

05:44.320 --> 05:46.527
Yeah, will you look around please?

05:47.556 --> 05:49.627
Hey, that's not bad at all.

05:50.659 --> 05:54.971
Hello? You have? Jack, you're a doll.

05:55.030 --> 05:57.032
Yeah, yeah, right away. Yeah.

05:57.099 --> 06:00.376
What does he do now?
Shoot himself out of a cannon?

06:03.939 --> 06:06.215
Say, that's a pretty elaborate
musical phrase, isn't it?

06:06.275 --> 06:08.118
- Well, it's a...
- Not that it bothers me, you understand.

06:08.177 --> 06:11.454
I gotta go pick up a book.
I'll talk to you later, Herb.

06:11.513 --> 06:13.151
Go ahead. Keep playing.

06:16.018 --> 06:17.395
He liked it.

06:17.853 --> 06:20.697
Oh, sure, I could tell he liked it.
He did everything but card tricks.

06:20.756 --> 06:22.633
- Now, Dick...
- No, brother, I've seen everything.

06:22.691 --> 06:25.467
Here I sit at this piano,
and this nutcracker...

06:25.527 --> 06:27.268
But, Dick, he's always like that.

06:27.329 --> 06:29.673
- Mrs. Hart. How are you?
- Hello, Herb.

06:29.732 --> 06:31.837
Well, introduce me to this nice young man.

06:31.901 --> 06:35.144
- This is Dick Rodgers.
- I'm very happy to meet you, Mrs. Hart.

06:35.204 --> 06:38.344
- That was you playing the songs?
- Yes.

06:38.407 --> 06:41.581
- You wrote them?
- Well, sure. He's a real composer.

06:41.644 --> 06:43.851
Isn't that nice?

06:43.913 --> 06:45.290
You know something?

06:45.347 --> 06:49.489
I like your songs
and your playing, very much.

06:49.551 --> 06:52.031
Well, thank you, Mrs. Hart.

06:52.087 --> 06:54.727
Here, what am I standing here for?
Have a bite.

06:57.993 --> 07:01.406
<i>For quite a while, I didn't hear from Larry
and it began to look as though</i>

07:01.463 --> 07:05.775
<i>neither my tunes nor I
had scored much of a hit with Mr. Hart.</i>

07:05.834 --> 07:07.404
<i>I stuck with it.</i>

07:07.469 --> 07:11.246
<i>But, believe me, a tune without a lyric
is a mighty lonesome thing.</i>

07:16.612 --> 07:17.784
Hello.

07:18.480 --> 07:20.084
Oh, hello, Herb.

07:20.516 --> 07:21.688
Yeah?

07:22.151 --> 07:24.427
- What?
- Yeah, yeah, you heard me.

07:24.486 --> 07:27.956
- He's crazy about the songs.
- Yeah, he's crazy all right.

07:28.023 --> 07:31.163
No, no, not just crazy.
He's crazy about the music.

07:31.226 --> 07:33.206
I haven't heard from him in two weeks.

07:33.262 --> 07:34.935
- He wrote a lyric.
- A lyric?

07:34.997 --> 07:37.409
A lyric. You know, words.

07:38.334 --> 07:41.144
<i>Be there at 5:30 sharp.
And don't be late, please.</i>

07:41.203 --> 07:42.705
<i>Okay, fine. Goodbye.</i>

07:46.442 --> 07:48.752
<i>5:30 came, 5:30 went.</i>

07:48.811 --> 07:50.256
<i>And I got my first introduction</i>

07:50.312 --> 07:52.952
<i>to something I soon learned
I could count on,</i>

07:53.015 --> 07:55.825
<i>the business of waiting for Larry.</i>

07:55.884 --> 07:58.455
- Now don't worry. He'll be here.
- So he's crazy about it, huh?

07:58.520 --> 08:02.400
I tell you, the guy called me and
he was jumping through the telephone.

08:04.026 --> 08:05.300
Hi, Herb.

08:09.631 --> 08:11.577
Morn! Morn! Mary!

08:12.368 --> 08:14.348
Herb, have you seen
the September issue of <i>Vanity Fair?</i>

08:14.403 --> 08:15.905
- The what?
- No, I can tell you haven't seen it.

08:15.971 --> 08:17.143
- What is it, dear?
- Mom, have you seen

08:17.206 --> 08:18.583
<i>the September issue of Vanity Fair?</i>

08:18.640 --> 08:20.210
- No, I haven't.
- Mary, what have you done with it?

08:20.275 --> 08:21.845
You know I don't
read that stuff, Mr. Larry.

08:21.910 --> 08:23.787
Can we find it, please? Can we find it?

08:23.846 --> 08:26.520
It's getting so you can't find anything
in this house anymore.

08:26.582 --> 08:28.289
- Hi, Dick.
- Hi, Larry.

08:28.350 --> 08:29.988
Play that first thing for me, will you?

08:30.052 --> 08:33.465
- What thing?
- You know.

08:33.522 --> 08:34.967
- Hey, I got a new rhyme for you.
- Yeah?

08:35.024 --> 08:36.230
Yeah, what rhymes with tapestry?

08:36.291 --> 08:38.861
- Tapestry?
- Half-past three. Please.

08:39.428 --> 08:40.907
I found it in your room, Mr. Larry.

08:40.962 --> 08:42.874
Oh, good. Boy, you're wonderful.
You're a doll.

08:42.931 --> 08:45.207
- Listen, get me something to eat, will you?
- It's near suppertime.

08:45.267 --> 08:47.543
There's some knockwurst and salami
in the packages there.

08:47.603 --> 08:49.105
Cut some up, please.

08:49.838 --> 08:52.079
Here we are. Here we are.

08:55.044 --> 08:56.853
That's it. There you are.

08:59.515 --> 09:01.188
<i>Manhattan.</i>

09:01.250 --> 09:03.856
- You like Manhattan?
- Manhattan? Yeah, yeah, I like Manhattan.

09:03.919 --> 09:05.330
<i>Manhattan.</i>

09:05.988 --> 09:07.626
<i>We've got Manhattan</i>

09:07.689 --> 09:11.296
<i>The Bronx and Staten Island, too</i>

09:11.360 --> 09:17.367
<i>It's lovely going through the zoo</i>

09:17.733 --> 09:20.145
You know the rest. Go ahead. Play it, Dick.

09:22.838 --> 09:24.840
<i>Summer journeys to Niagara</i>

09:24.907 --> 09:28.480
<i>And to other places
aggravate all our cares</i>

09:28.544 --> 09:30.888
<i>We'll save our fares</i>

09:30.946 --> 09:35.122
<i>I've a cozy little flat in what
is known as old Manhattan</i>

09:35.184 --> 09:38.222
<i>We'll settle down</i>

09:38.287 --> 09:41.666
<i>Right here in town</i>

09:42.691 --> 09:44.637
<i>We'll have Manhattan</i>

09:44.693 --> 09:48.436
<i>The Bronx and Staten Island, too</i>

09:48.497 --> 09:55.073
<i>It's lovely going through the zoo</i>

09:57.506 --> 10:03.218
<i>It's very fancy
on old Delancey Street, you know</i>

10:03.278 --> 10:07.021
<i>The subway charms us so</i>

10:07.082 --> 10:12.464
<i>When balmy breezes blow to and fro</i>

10:12.521 --> 10:18.233
<i>And tell me what street
compares with Matt Street in July</i>

10:18.293 --> 10:25.040
<i>Sweet pushcarts gently gliding by</i>

10:25.901 --> 10:30.577
<i>The great big city's a wondrous toy</i>

10:30.639 --> 10:35.816
<i>Just made for a girl and boy</i>

10:35.878 --> 10:38.518
<i>We'll turn Manhattan</i>

10:38.580 --> 10:42.790
<i>Into an isle of joy</i>

10:49.191 --> 10:54.402
<i>I'd like to take a sail
on Jamaica Bay with you</i>

10:54.463 --> 11:01.381
<i>And fair Canarsie's lakes we'll view</i>

11:01.436 --> 11:08.217
<i>The city's clamor can never spoil</i>

11:08.277 --> 11:14.523
<i>The dreams of a boy and girl</i>

11:15.717 --> 11:19.290
<i>We'll turn Manhattan</i>

11:19.354 --> 11:25.566
<i>Into an isle of joy</i>

11:26.895 --> 11:30.172
Well, it's nice,
but a bit off the beaten track. I'm sorry.

11:31.166 --> 11:32.839
<i>But when you're riding the crest of youth,</i>

11:32.901 --> 11:35.939
<i>you don't get easily upset,
even by turndowns.</i>

11:36.004 --> 11:40.214
<i>Larry, in particular, was tireless,
and his enthusiasm was boundless.</i>

11:40.475 --> 11:45.185
<i>This kind of netter-sireiter writing, singing,
demonstrating went on for two years.</i>

11:45.447 --> 11:47.256
<i>But nothing happened.</i>

11:47.316 --> 11:50.820
<i>They aH thought the songs
were fresh, different, engaging,</i>

11:50.886 --> 11:52.456
<i>but nobody bought them.</i>

11:52.521 --> 11:54.762
<i>And after a while, this gets monotonous.</i>

11:54.823 --> 11:57.099
<i>After two years, it can get desperate.</i>

11:57.893 --> 12:01.033
<i>Finally, when I felt
I couldn't take it any longer,</i>

12:01.096 --> 12:03.042
<i>I had a talk with my father.</i>

12:05.234 --> 12:07.043
Can I help, Richard?

12:07.903 --> 12:11.009
What would you say if I told you
I were giving up being a composer?

12:11.073 --> 12:13.576
I'd say all right,
if I could think of a good reason,

12:13.642 --> 12:15.417
but just offhand I can't think of one.

12:15.477 --> 12:18.424
Well, I'll give you one. Nothing happens.

12:18.480 --> 12:21.051
Two years, almost three and I'm nowhere.

12:21.116 --> 12:24.962
- Where do you want to be?
- What's the sense of kidding, Pop?

12:25.020 --> 12:27.057
You've been carrying the freight too long.

12:27.122 --> 12:29.625
College, Academy of Music, and now this.

12:29.691 --> 12:32.137
Months and months
of knocking our brains out.

12:32.194 --> 12:33.571
Nobody cares.

12:33.629 --> 12:35.802
I think you've written many good things.

12:35.864 --> 12:39.277
Sure, and they can't even get me
a cup of coffee.

12:39.334 --> 12:41.473
Well, Richard, the coffee will come.

12:41.536 --> 12:44.176
Maybe you have to boil it a little more.

12:44.239 --> 12:48.813
- No, it's no good. I'm going into business.
- Business? Doing what?

12:48.877 --> 12:50.754
Selling infants' wear.

12:50.812 --> 12:53.520
How did you happen to
select this vocation?

12:53.582 --> 12:56.620
Well, a friend of mine
offered me $50 a week to start.

12:56.685 --> 12:57.891
Well!

12:57.953 --> 13:01.765
I never knew you were so interested
in getting $50 a week.

13:01.823 --> 13:05.828
- Do you need $50?
- What I need is self-respect.

13:05.894 --> 13:07.931
Well, you sound desperate.

13:07.996 --> 13:10.977
Gee, Pop. It's not only living off you.

13:11.033 --> 13:13.570
But I'm getting so
I'm envious of everyone.

13:13.635 --> 13:17.412
A counterman,
a taxi driver, a shoe shiner.

13:17.472 --> 13:19.611
Anybody who can earn anything.

13:19.675 --> 13:23.521
Richard, I went through
four years of college,

13:23.578 --> 13:26.559
two years of med school,
interned for two more years.

13:26.615 --> 13:28.185
And just about that time,

13:28.250 --> 13:31.561
I was in the same place
as any kid leaving grammar school,

13:31.620 --> 13:35.124
except I had a slight added handicap.

13:35.190 --> 13:37.568
I was also in love with your mother.

13:37.626 --> 13:42.302
Sol can only tell you, Son,
just keep writing those nice songs.

13:42.364 --> 13:43.775
Work with Larry.

13:43.832 --> 13:46.813
Dream a little longer,
and work a little harder.

13:46.868 --> 13:48.347
Be a little patient.

13:49.638 --> 13:53.142
No, it's no good, Pop.
I've made up my mind.

13:53.208 --> 13:58.055
Well, nothing better for a man than to
finally know exactly what he wants to do.

13:59.881 --> 14:02.862
So, I guess that's the way it's gotta be.

14:02.918 --> 14:04.864
Hope you don't think
I'm running out on you, Larry.

14:04.920 --> 14:06.297
Don't be silly.

14:06.355 --> 14:08.892
Of course, it is quite a switch
from musical comedy,

14:08.957 --> 14:11.403
but I think the diaper business
is a good business.

14:11.460 --> 14:13.462
Want something to eat?
Something to drink? Cigar?

14:13.528 --> 14:16.475
- No, thanks.
- That's right, you don't smoke, do you?

14:16.531 --> 14:18.704
Let's have a party. Want to have a party?

14:18.767 --> 14:21.611
It's an occasion. Might wind up
the greatest party we ever had.

14:21.670 --> 14:24.412
A farewell party.
Farewell to the maestro of music

14:24.473 --> 14:26.885
and a welcome
to the mogul of baby clothes, huh?

14:35.350 --> 14:37.193
Come on, now.

14:38.687 --> 14:40.826
Look out. Hot coffee.
Hot coffee coming through.

14:40.889 --> 14:43.028
Harry, how about you? A little coffee, boy?

14:43.091 --> 14:44.468
That's right. Just fresh made.

14:44.526 --> 14:46.802
- Hey, Larry, how about some more coffee?
- It'll stunt your growth.

14:46.862 --> 14:49.240
No, I'm sorry.
In that corner you get no coffee.

14:49.297 --> 14:50.970
- Good evening, Mr. Eddie.
- Hi, Mary. How are you?

14:51.032 --> 14:52.477
- Fine.
- Miss Grant. Miss McNeil.

14:52.534 --> 14:54.514
- Hello, Mary.
- Good evening. May I take your wraps?

14:54.569 --> 14:58.176
- Hey, a party.
- Now, Mr. Eddie.

14:58.240 --> 15:00.117
- Hey, Eddie. Hi!
- Hi, everybody. Hi!

15:00.175 --> 15:02.746
- Hey, hi, baby. Where you been?
- Auditioning.

15:02.811 --> 15:06.588
- Tough year for singers, you know.
- It's a tough year. Period.

15:06.648 --> 15:10.790
Or maybe not. Will you have some coffee?

15:10.852 --> 15:12.957
- Thanks.
- Let's assume this is for you.

15:13.021 --> 15:15.058
Look, this is my house.
Don't I get to meet the...

15:15.123 --> 15:19.697
Oh, sure, sure.
Everybody gets to meet everybody.

15:19.761 --> 15:23.140
Ladies and gentlemen,
I want you to meet two protégées of mine,

15:23.198 --> 15:26.805
Miss Margo Grant and Miss Peggy McNeil.

15:28.570 --> 15:31.073
Say, Herb,
you know Eddie Anders, of course?

15:31.139 --> 15:33.415
Of course. May I say
there's no one I'd rather hear sing?

15:33.475 --> 15:36.422
- Well, how about a song now, huh, kid?
- Oh, not now. Later maybe.

15:36.478 --> 15:38.890
What I really want
is for you to hear this one.

15:38.947 --> 15:41.621
She sings, too? What are we waiting for?

15:41.683 --> 15:44.289
Gee, let me catch my breath.
A little later maybe.

15:44.352 --> 15:46.423
What is this,
singers want to sing a little later, maybe?

15:46.488 --> 15:48.729
Come here, honey. I want to talk to you.

15:48.790 --> 15:52.328
- You're a singer, too?
- Well, not exactly. I dance.

15:52.394 --> 15:53.873
Yes, of course.

15:53.929 --> 15:56.375
May I say
there's no one I'd rather dance with?

15:57.265 --> 16:00.178
- Ah-ah, ah-ah, ah-ah.
-"Ah-ah, ah-ah," what?

16:00.235 --> 16:02.044
This one is for the boy.

16:05.440 --> 16:09.388
- Tell me all about yourself.
- Well, there's really not much to tell.

16:10.512 --> 16:13.254
That's a wonderful song.

16:13.315 --> 16:14.726
I'm glad you like it.

16:14.783 --> 16:18.128
I had no idea it was that good
when we wrote it.

16:18.186 --> 16:20.962
- Oh, are you...
- Larry Hart. Yeah, I wrote the words.

16:21.022 --> 16:22.262
Really?

16:23.558 --> 16:27.734
- Do you sing for a living?
- Kind of. I work in a café.

16:28.296 --> 16:30.298
It's really a Speakeasy.

16:30.365 --> 16:33.642
- Have you been here long?
- No. I'm hot out of Boston.

16:33.702 --> 16:36.205
- Have you ever been in a show?
- A couple.

16:36.271 --> 16:38.410
Why? Are you looking for someone
for a show?

16:38.473 --> 16:41.545
Because if you are,
they call me "Available" McNeil.

16:41.610 --> 16:43.749
No, honey. We're looking for a producer.

16:43.812 --> 16:45.587
- You know any?
- Producers?

16:45.647 --> 16:47.320
- What are they?
- Yeah.

16:47.382 --> 16:50.363
I never got past the elevator boy.

16:50.418 --> 16:54.560
Well, if either one of us
ever find a producer to produce our show,

16:54.623 --> 16:56.500
I'll bet you'd be wonderful in it.

16:56.558 --> 16:58.504
<i>You mean me?</i>

16:58.560 --> 17:00.938
I'll bet you'd be the best thing in it.

17:03.732 --> 17:07.680
- Shall we dance?
- Yeah. Sure. Come on.

17:12.173 --> 17:16.315
So you're a little fellow, aren't you?
But on you, it's very becoming.

17:20.781 --> 17:22.819
That's another song
from our un-produced show.

17:22.884 --> 17:24.227
I know and I love it.

17:24.286 --> 17:26.425
- You do?
- Eddie taught it to me.

17:26.488 --> 17:28.126
Well, what are we waiting for?

17:28.890 --> 17:30.767
Excuse me just a minute,
will you, honey, please?

17:30.825 --> 17:33.533
Thank you. Pardon me, Dick. Everybody.

17:34.396 --> 17:36.637
From the un-produced works
of Rodgers and Hart,

17:36.698 --> 17:39.008
Miss Peggy McNeil is going to sing
an unknown song entitled

17:39.067 --> 17:40.410
<i>There's A Small Hotel.</i>

17:40.468 --> 17:42.641
Miss McNeil, Mr. Rodgers.
Mr. Rodgers, Miss McNeil.

17:42.704 --> 17:45.617
- How do you do?
- I hope you all like it. You're on, honey.

17:49.277 --> 17:54.056
<i>There's a small hotel</i>

17:54.115 --> 17:58.222
<i>With a wishing well</i>

17:58.286 --> 18:03.235
<i>I wish that we were there</i>

18:03.291 --> 18:06.500
<i>Together</i>

18:08.797 --> 18:13.507
<i>There's a bridal suite</i>

18:13.568 --> 18:18.244
<i>One room bright and neat</i>

18:18.306 --> 18:22.721
<i>Complete far us ta share</i>

18:22.777 --> 18:26.486
<i>Together</i>

18:28.249 --> 18:31.856
<i>Looking through the window</i>

18:31.920 --> 18:37.336
<i>You can see a distant steeple</i>

18:38.460 --> 18:42.135
<i>Not a sign of people</i>

18:43.098 --> 18:46.841
<i>Who wants people?</i>

18:48.103 --> 18:52.848
<i>When the steeple bell</i>

18:52.907 --> 18:57.913
<i>Says, "Good night, sleep well"</i>

18:57.979 --> 19:01.756
<i>We'll thank the small hotel</i>

19:01.816 --> 19:06.890
<i>We'll creep into our little shell</i>

19:06.955 --> 19:12.906
<i>And we will thank the small hotel</i>

19:13.695 --> 19:19.646
<i>Together</i>

19:21.569 --> 19:23.276
- How about that, Herb?
- Oh, that was great.

19:23.338 --> 19:25.784
You really got something here, Eddie.

19:25.840 --> 19:29.287
- You do sing awful good, Peggy.
- It's an awful good song.

19:29.344 --> 19:32.154
There's another one.
We've got a million of them.

19:32.213 --> 19:33.749
And I'll bet you could sing them all.

19:33.815 --> 19:37.058
Wouldn't it get kind of monotonous,
me singing all those songs?

19:37.118 --> 19:39.564
No, honey, not to me it wouldn't.

19:41.956 --> 19:45.563
Peggy, how tall are you?

19:45.627 --> 19:48.233
I don't know. About 5'4", I guess.

19:48.296 --> 19:49.900
That's what I figured.

19:58.139 --> 19:59.641
There we are.

20:00.909 --> 20:03.753
- What is this?
- I'm filing you away for future reference.

20:03.812 --> 20:06.691
This is Dick, he's 6',
this is Herb, this is my mother.

20:06.748 --> 20:09.661
This is a little girl named Helen
and this is the milkman.

20:09.718 --> 20:11.288
I don't think I quite understand.

20:11.352 --> 20:13.389
You will, after you've known me
10 or 15 years.

20:13.455 --> 20:16.231
Larry! Larry! Larry! Dick!

20:16.291 --> 20:18.464
Look, you know what happened?
It's the darnedest thing.

20:18.526 --> 20:20.972
Look. Dick! Dick! Mr. Kay just phoned.

20:21.029 --> 20:22.872
- Mr. who?
- Mr. Kay.

20:22.931 --> 20:25.377
- The Theatre Guild. They want us.
- Who wants us?

20:25.433 --> 20:27.242
The Theatre Guild.
They want us to do a show.

20:27.302 --> 20:29.179
- The Garrick Gaieties.
- Oh, yeah. I heard about that.

20:29.237 --> 20:31.683
The kids are putting on
some kind of a benefit to buy tapestries

20:31.740 --> 20:34.277
- for the Guild's new theater.
- But, Dick, it's the Theatre Guild.

20:34.342 --> 20:37.482
- But it's only another benefit.
- Well, can't we talk it over, anyway, huh?

20:37.545 --> 20:40.025
Watch me change the mogul
of baby clothes back into a musician.

20:40.081 --> 20:42.152
Wanna bet? Come on. Come on.

20:42.951 --> 20:44.089
<i>And darned if he didn't.</i>

20:44.152 --> 20:48.794
<i>So there it was in big, bright lights,
The Garrick Gaieties.</i>

21:02.237 --> 21:05.707
<i>On the first of May</i>

21:05.774 --> 21:09.085
<i>It is moving day</i>

21:09.144 --> 21:12.523
<i>Spring is here so blow your job</i>

21:12.580 --> 21:16.118
<i>Throw your job away</i>

21:16.184 --> 21:19.961
<i>Now's the time to trust</i>

21:20.021 --> 21:24.128
<i>To your Wanderlust</i>

21:24.192 --> 21:28.368
<i>In the city's dust you wait</i>

21:28.429 --> 21:31.308
<i>Must you wait?</i>

21:31.366 --> 21:35.007
<i>Just you wait</i>

21:35.069 --> 21:37.743
<i>In a mountain greenery</i>

21:37.806 --> 21:40.980
<i>Where God paints the scenery</i>

21:41.042 --> 21:45.491
<i>Just two crazy people together</i>

21:45.547 --> 21:47.754
<i>While you love your lover</i>

21:47.816 --> 21:51.263
<i>Let blue skies be your coverlet</i>

21:51.319 --> 21:54.630
<i>When it rains, we don't mind the weather</i>

21:54.689 --> 21:57.169
<i>And if you're good</i>

21:57.225 --> 21:59.899
<i>I'll search for wood</i>

21:59.961 --> 22:02.407
<i>$0 you can cook</i>

22:02.463 --> 22:05.740
<i>While I stand looking</i>

22:05.800 --> 22:10.909
<i>Beans could get no keener reception
in a beanery</i>

22:10.972 --> 22:17.048
<i>Bless our mountain greenery home</i>

22:24.719 --> 22:26.790
<i>When the world was young</i>

22:26.855 --> 22:29.233
<i>Old Father Adam with sin would grapple</i>

22:29.290 --> 22:31.497
<i>So we're entitled to just one apple</i>

22:31.559 --> 22:33.698
<i>I mean, to make apple sauce</i>

22:34.629 --> 22:36.734
<i>Underneath the bough</i>

22:36.798 --> 22:39.278
<i>We'll learn a lesson from Mister Omar</i>

22:39.334 --> 22:41.507
<i>Beneath the eyes of no Pa and no Ma</i>

22:41.569 --> 22:43.378
<i>Old Lady Nature is boss</i>

22:43.438 --> 22:45.975
<i>And if you're good</i>

22:46.040 --> 22:48.384
<i>I'll search for wood</i>

22:48.443 --> 22:50.787
<i>$0 you can cook</i>

22:50.845 --> 22:54.054
<i>While I stand looking</i>

22:54.115 --> 22:58.894
<i>Beans could get no keener reception
in a beanery</i>

22:58.953 --> 23:03.368
<i>Bless our mountain greenery home</i>

23:49.504 --> 23:51.541
<i>Simple cooking means</i>

23:51.606 --> 23:53.711
<i>More than French cuisines</i>

23:53.775 --> 23:58.417
<i>I've a banquet planned
which is sandwiches and beans</i>

23:58.479 --> 24:00.720
<i>Coffee's just as grand</i>

24:00.782 --> 24:02.728
<i>With a little sand</i>

24:02.784 --> 24:05.731
<i>Eat and you'll grow fatter, boy</i>

24:07.355 --> 24:10.393
<i>Shatter, boy?</i>

24:10.458 --> 24:13.996
<i>Attaboy</i>

24:22.770 --> 24:24.647
<i>In a mountain greenery</i>

24:24.706 --> 24:26.743
<i>Where God paints the scenery</i>

24:26.808 --> 24:30.688
<i>Just two crazy people together</i>

24:30.745 --> 24:32.952
<i>How we love sequestering</i>

24:33.014 --> 24:35.119
<i>Where no pests are pestering</i>

24:35.183 --> 24:38.460
<i>No dear Mama holds us in tether</i>

24:38.519 --> 24:42.661
<i>Mosquitoes here won't bite you, dear</i>

24:42.724 --> 24:47.639
<i>I'll let them sting me on the finger</i>

24:47.695 --> 24:51.905
<i>We could find no cleaner retreat
from life's machinery</i>

24:51.966 --> 24:54.037
<i>Than our mountain greenery home</i>

24:54.102 --> 24:56.048
<i>Down with city slickings</i>

24:56.104 --> 24:58.209
<i>Up with cows and chickens</i>

24:58.272 --> 25:00.343
<i>Down with noise and clutter</i>

25:00.408 --> 25:02.479
<i>Up with milk and butter</i>

25:02.543 --> 25:05.353
<i>Down with life's machinery</i>

25:05.413 --> 25:10.863
<i>Bless our mountain greenery</i>

25:10.918 --> 25:17.335
<i>home!</i>

25:35.410 --> 25:37.822
- Hi, Eddie.
- Hi, Mr. Hart. Here's your morning papers.

25:37.879 --> 25:39.449
- Three of each.
- Yeah. How much do I owe you?

25:39.514 --> 25:41.653
- That'll be 24 cents for the works.
- 24 cents?

25:41.716 --> 25:44.697
24 cents I haven't got, but here's a buck.
Buy yourself a railroad.

25:44.752 --> 25:46.993
- Gee, thanks!
- That's all right, Eddie.

25:47.055 --> 25:49.934
Hey, Morn! Morn!

25:49.991 --> 25:52.767
- The papers are here.
- Coffee is ready, Lorry.

25:52.827 --> 25:55.000
Just a minute, will you, darling?
Just a minute.

25:55.063 --> 25:56.838
Here it is, here it is.

25:56.898 --> 25:59.003
"Last night a group
of the younger Theatre Guild actors

25:59.067 --> 26:01.673
"came up with a little hand-built revue
called The Garrick Gaieties.

26:01.736 --> 26:03.841
"And to my utter amazement,
I found it jammed throughout

26:03.905 --> 26:08.285
"with talented young people, bright tunes,
sparkling lyrics and smart sketches."

26:08.342 --> 26:11.585
- Mom, we're in. We're a hit.
- But naturally, Lorry.

26:11.646 --> 26:13.182
I'll get that.

26:17.985 --> 26:19.987
- Good morning, Richard.
- Hello, darling.

26:20.054 --> 26:21.158
Have you heard the good news?

26:21.222 --> 26:23.964
- We're a hit. We're in.
- But of course.

26:24.025 --> 26:25.299
And if the Theatre Guild has any notions

26:25.359 --> 26:28.465
about this little show running for just a
few performances, they'd better forget it.

26:28.529 --> 26:29.599
- Hi.
- Hi.

26:29.664 --> 26:30.734
- Uh-oh.
-"Uh-oh," what?

26:30.798 --> 26:32.243
-"The music."
- What about the music?

26:32.300 --> 26:34.906
"The music," it says here,
"is fresh and melodic and engaging,

26:34.969 --> 26:37.745
"and these qualities are bound to carry
composer Richard Rodgers to the top

26:37.805 --> 26:39.182
"in years to come.

26:39.240 --> 26:43.052
"Meanwhile, by the way,
just who is Mr. Richard Rodgers?"

26:43.111 --> 26:45.352
Mr. Richard Rodgers
is the young gentleman

26:45.413 --> 26:47.017
who is making my coffee get cold.

26:47.081 --> 26:48.424
Now just a minute, Mrs. Hart.

26:48.483 --> 26:51.327
I want to prove to you
that Larry isn't so famous, either.

26:51.385 --> 26:52.830
-"The lyrics."
- What about the lyrics?

26:52.887 --> 26:55.697
"The lyrics are bright, witty and adult
and in good taste.

26:55.756 --> 26:57.360
"In short, they are excellent.

26:57.425 --> 27:01.100
"And it is a pleasure to greet a new writer
as gifted as he is unknown,

27:01.162 --> 27:03.108
"Mr. Lorenz Hart."

27:03.164 --> 27:05.371
- Mr. Hart.
- Mr. Rodgers.

27:05.433 --> 27:06.878
I'll get it.

27:10.204 --> 27:11.444
- Hiya, Morn.
- Hello, Eddie.

27:11.506 --> 27:14.851
Have you seen the notices?
They're terrific. Morn, we're a smash.

27:14.909 --> 27:16.650
- But certainly.
- Hi, Dick. Hi, Larry.

27:16.711 --> 27:19.055
Have you seen what's in the papers
here about Herbie Fields?

27:19.113 --> 27:20.956
- No. What does it say?
- Oh, boy, it says right here,

27:21.015 --> 27:23.222
"The original sketches were concocted

27:23.284 --> 27:26.231
"by a young man nobody ever heard of,
Herbert Fields.

27:26.287 --> 27:30.326
"Outstanding in a smart cast
was singer Eddie Anders who will be..."

27:30.391 --> 27:32.894
- Eddie Anders? Hey, that's me!
- Congratulations.

27:32.960 --> 27:35.270
- You're in, Eddie!
- I'll get it. I'll get it.

27:38.633 --> 27:39.941
Good morning, Herb.

27:40.001 --> 27:41.981
Oh, you bet it's a good morning.
Have you heard the news?

27:42.036 --> 27:44.539
- Sure. We are smash.
- Yes, that's right. We are.

27:44.605 --> 27:45.948
- Hi, fellows.
- Hi, Herbie.

27:46.007 --> 27:47.042
Have you read these write-ups?

27:47.108 --> 27:48.451
- They're the most sensational...
- Yeah, I read them.

27:48.509 --> 27:49.852
- Well, what's the matter?
- Nothing's the matter.

27:49.911 --> 27:51.447
- Everything's fine.
- What is it? What is it?

27:51.512 --> 27:53.082
James Kelly.
He wants to produce a show.

27:53.147 --> 27:55.058
- What? Kelly?
- Yes, I was up all night with him.

27:55.116 --> 27:57.460
He saw the Gaieties last night
and he wants to do a show with us.

27:57.518 --> 27:59.327
- On Broadway?
- Not in Bridgeport!

27:59.387 --> 28:00.866
- That's great.
- What are we waiting for?

28:00.922 --> 28:02.595
Mom, cook some breakfast,
will you, please?

28:02.657 --> 28:04.659
Mary. Mary, honey,
cook some breakfast, too.

28:04.725 --> 28:06.102
We'll start right away. 3:00 sharp.

28:06.160 --> 28:08.367
<i>We've already got My Funny Valentine
and You're Nearer.</i>

28:08.429 --> 28:09.840
- What time is it?
- 9:30.

28:09.897 --> 28:11.240
9:30. I've got to make a phone call.

28:11.299 --> 28:12.972
Talk to yourselves, will you?

28:15.102 --> 28:17.605
Hello. Give me Trafalgar 2098, please.

28:21.209 --> 28:22.279
Hello.

28:22.343 --> 28:25.415
<i>Hello. Hello. Is this my blue-eyed friend
from Boston?</i>

28:25.479 --> 28:27.823
This is your red-eyed friend from Boston.

28:27.882 --> 28:30.692
- Who is it?
- This is Larry. Larry Hart, yeah.

28:30.751 --> 28:32.731
Now, look, don't get excited.
Don't even wake up.

28:32.787 --> 28:34.824
You're dreaming this, only it's true.

28:34.889 --> 28:36.926
<i>We sold our musical comedy.</i>

28:36.991 --> 28:41.030
Gee, Larry, that's marvelous,
really and truly.

28:41.095 --> 28:43.234
You're going to be in it, hear me?

28:44.432 --> 28:46.036
<i>I'll see you at the club tonight.</i>

28:46.100 --> 28:48.080
And I'm gonna bring
Herb and Dick with me.

28:49.770 --> 28:53.343
And aside from that,
I don't know anything new.

28:53.407 --> 28:55.216
Thank you, Larry.

28:55.276 --> 28:58.257
Larry, I'd like to measure you right now.

28:58.312 --> 29:01.691
I'll bet you're really taller. I know I am.

29:02.016 --> 29:10.016
<i>Goodbye.</i>

29:27.508 --> 29:30.921
There you are, sir,
and if I do say so myself, they look fine.

29:33.681 --> 29:36.161
- They look all right, huh?
- Oh, yes, sir.

29:36.217 --> 29:37.355
Get up.

29:40.421 --> 29:41.866
Go ahead, walk.

29:43.257 --> 29:46.136
One, two, three, four.

29:46.193 --> 29:50.505
One, two, three, four,
turn, two, three, four.

29:52.266 --> 29:57.511
They feel fine, but I feel
as if I were walking downhill, you know?

29:57.571 --> 29:59.073
Well, naturally.

30:01.175 --> 30:04.019
- What about the trousers?
- Oh, yes. You see, I forgot to tell you.

30:04.078 --> 30:06.251
When the lifts move you up,

30:06.314 --> 30:09.227
the trousers, shall we say,
move up proportionately.

30:10.184 --> 30:13.427
- However, with a slight adjustment...
- Slight adjustment?

30:17.291 --> 30:19.771
You're completely defeating your purpose.

30:21.295 --> 30:24.105
Well, they feel very comfortable,

30:24.165 --> 30:26.543
- but I get a little... In the back of it.
- Oh, yes.

30:26.600 --> 30:29.137
For a while, you'll notice a slight
tenseness in those back muscles.

30:29.203 --> 30:32.082
However, after a while,
that too will adjust itself.

30:32.139 --> 30:34.016
- Look all right?
- Oh, excellent, sir.

30:34.075 --> 30:36.351
Oh, I must warn you.
When you take your shoes off at night,

30:36.410 --> 30:39.823
if you notice a slight popping of the ears,
don't let it alarm you.

30:44.985 --> 30:47.727
- 3:00 sharp, huh?
- Well, you know Larry.

30:47.788 --> 30:50.098
Here it is 5:15, he's not here yet.

31:07.375 --> 31:09.252
Hiya, baby. Hiya, kid.

31:10.444 --> 31:13.186
Notice anything different? Look, you guys.

31:13.247 --> 31:14.555
- Haircut?
- No.

31:14.615 --> 31:16.526
- Shave?
- No. Well?

31:16.584 --> 31:19.258
- Well, what?
- Well, what? The shoes. Look.

31:19.320 --> 31:20.628
- The shoes?
- Certainly. The shoes.

31:20.688 --> 31:21.860
2" taller. How about that?

31:21.922 --> 31:23.094
- Taller?
- Sure.

31:23.157 --> 31:24.795
- Are you serious?
- Certainly. 2".

31:24.859 --> 31:26.861
No kidding. Built up on the inside.
You can't even see it.

31:26.927 --> 31:28.873
You ought to get some sometime.
Anybody call?

31:28.929 --> 31:30.602
Peggy-
- Yeah?

31:30.664 --> 31:32.666
Say, we've got to go over to the club
and see her tonight.

31:32.733 --> 31:34.576
And is she excited about doing the show.

31:34.635 --> 31:36.342
- What show?
- What show?

31:36.404 --> 31:38.782
Why, our new show, of course.

31:38.839 --> 31:40.682
Why? Does she want to be in the chorus?

31:40.741 --> 31:43.153
Chorus? Why, she's going to do the part.

31:43.844 --> 31:45.517
You both like her, don't you?

31:45.579 --> 31:48.389
Oh, sure, but, Larry,
this isn't The Garrick Gaieties.

31:48.449 --> 31:50.986
- Did you ever hear of Joyce Harmon?
- Yeah. Certainly.

31:51.051 --> 31:53.122
Well, Mr. Kelly's got her signed
to a personal contract.

31:53.187 --> 31:54.928
That's one of the main reasons
he's doing our show,

31:54.989 --> 31:56.525
because she's right for it.

32:00.327 --> 32:02.273
Why, Joyce Harmon's
the greatest thing you've ever seen.

32:02.329 --> 32:04.366
Yeah, I know. But you said that she was...

32:04.432 --> 32:06.503
Look, Larry, we're not producing the show.

32:06.567 --> 32:08.843
A man investing that much money
in a couple of new authors,

32:08.903 --> 32:11.747
he wants some protection.
You can understand that.

32:13.107 --> 32:16.111
Yeah. I can understand that.

32:17.244 --> 32:20.020
<i>Oh, the wild herd gathers
where the moon is full</i>

32:20.080 --> 32:22.720
<i>There's not much buffalo but lots of bull</i>

32:22.783 --> 32:24.228
<i>Way out West</i>

32:24.985 --> 32:27.522
<i>In the wild, wild West</i>

32:27.588 --> 32:30.865
<i>Away out West on West End Avenue</i>

32:30.925 --> 32:33.269
<i>Yippee-ay-yay! You!</i>

32:39.533 --> 32:42.275
Well, tell me all about it.

32:43.304 --> 32:45.250
- Drinks are on me tonight.
- Oh.

32:45.306 --> 32:46.546
25% off.

32:50.778 --> 32:52.689
Well, herds to our show.

32:53.347 --> 32:55.884
- Peggy...
- What's wrong, Larry?

32:55.950 --> 32:58.123
Nothing the matter with the show?

32:58.185 --> 33:01.064
After I talked to you this morning,
I talked to Dick and Herb,

33:01.121 --> 33:04.625
and it seems as though the producer
has Joyce Harmon under contract and...

33:04.692 --> 33:07.070
- She's going to do the part.
- Yeah.

33:07.561 --> 33:09.404
I'm awfully sorry, Peggy.

33:09.463 --> 33:12.740
It's going to take all the boot
out of doing this show, for me, anyway.

33:12.800 --> 33:15.110
Don't worry. It's not so bad.

33:16.270 --> 33:19.080
I got a call this afternoon
from the Shubert office.

33:19.139 --> 33:22.143
They want me to go on the road
with some operetta.

33:22.209 --> 33:25.986
It's not the greatest part in the world,
but the money's pretty good

33:26.046 --> 33:28.424
and I guess I could use the experience.

33:29.850 --> 33:33.525
Peggy, this isn't the time,

33:33.587 --> 33:36.727
but ever since I saw you...

33:36.790 --> 33:38.269
Larry, please.

33:39.760 --> 33:44.072
We're both a little off-balance now,
and we both have many things to do.

33:45.633 --> 33:47.112
I know I have.

33:48.068 --> 33:49.513
Well, I went on record, anyway.

33:49.570 --> 33:51.880
Let's drink some of this before it gets flat.

33:59.680 --> 34:01.023
<i>That was the touch-off spark</i>

34:01.081 --> 34:03.493
<i>that was to affect
everything Larry Hart ever did again.</i>

34:05.085 --> 34:06.564
<i>But, frankly, I was more concerned</i>

34:06.620 --> 34:11.228
<i>with our new musical comedy
and our new leading lady.</i>

34:45.525 --> 34:48.473
<i>Fortune never smiles, but in my case</i>

34:48.529 --> 34:51.998
<i>It just laughs right in my face</i>

34:52.600 --> 34:55.978
<i>If} looked for a horseshoe, I suppose</i>

34:56.036 --> 35:01.076
<i>It would bop me right in the nose</i>

35:01.141 --> 35:04.213
<i>My luck will vary surely</i>

35:04.278 --> 35:09.023
<i>That's purely a curse</i>

35:09.083 --> 35:11.063
<i>My luck has changed</i>

35:11.118 --> 35:16.727
<i>It's gotten from rotten</i>

35:16.790 --> 35:19.532
<i>to worse</i>

35:21.128 --> 35:25.702
<i>Where's that rainbow you hear about?</i>

